Let the volume of the balloon equal $V$ and the pressure equal $P$. Since the volume is inversely proportional to the pressure, the product $VP$ must be equal to some constant, say $k$. Given the original conditions with a volume of $6\times10^{2}$ cubic meters and pressure of $4\times10^{3}$ pascals, we can write:
\begin{align*}
(6\times10^{2})(4\times10^{3})&=k\\
\Rightarrow\qquad k&=24\times10^{5}=2.4\times10^{6}
\end{align*}
Now, we are asked to find the volume when the pressure is increased to 500 times the original pressure. The new pressure is $500 \times 4\times10^{3} = 2000\times10^{3} = 2\times10^{6}$ pascals. Using the inverse relationship:
\begin{align*}
V \cdot (2\times10^{6})&=k\\
\Rightarrow\qquad V&=\frac{k}{2\times10^{6}}\\
&=\frac{2.4\times10^{6}}{2\times10^{6}}\\
&=\frac{2.4}{2}\\
&=1.2\text{ cubic meters}\\
&=1.2\times10^{0}\text{ cubic meters}
\end{align*}
Therefore, we have $c=1.2$ and $d=0$, so $c+d = 1.2 + 0 = 1.2$.

